{
  "texts": [
    "While we have presently focused on the near-complete or complete homogeneity of GPT-3.5's \"correct answers,\" we note that the \"correct answer\" effect may also encompass GPT-3.5's tendency to sometimes respond to different conditions of a given input much more predeterminedly than did human subjects, though still not uniformly.",
    "To illustrate, consider GPT-3.5's unprecedentedly large effect (d = 9.25) in the same direction with the findings of Hsee (1998) and of Many Labs 2.",
    "Different runs of GPT-3.5 thought the \"correct answer\" was that the higher-price variant of an inexpensive item (scarf) should be seen as more generous than lowerprice variant of an expensive item (coat) to a much more predetermined degree than did human subjects.",
    "We conducted an exploratory follow-up study for each of the six studies where a central-variable question was answered with a homogeneous \"correct answer.\"",
    "In each of our followup conditions, we presented the answer choices for the question with the homogeneous \"correct answer\" in the reverse order of our original condition to test for potential order effects."
  ]
}